annotation.TEXT: The “liquid metal” required groundbreaking CGI to depict. The film won an Oscar for special effects.
Actor Harvey Keitel has given acclaimed performances in films by directors Martin Scorsese, Ridley Scott, and Quentin Tarantino, among others.
Redbook is a women’s magazine with articles on marriage, beauty, recipes, etc. It was so named, the founding editor said, because red was a cheerful, bright color.
This is part of the theme song for Texaco Star Theater, sponsored by the oil company. In the ‘60s Texaco used the ad jingle “You can trust your car to the man who wears the star.”
1313 Mockingbird Lane was the address of the gothic home where the Munsters lived. It was a set on the Universal backlot, originally built for the 1946 film So Goes My Love.
In a 2011 interview, Gordon said he was not allowed to film in the Caverns, so he used split screens with still photos he took himself for these scenes.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Charles Schwab, one of the largest discount brokerages in the world, was originally called First Commander.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Charlie Callas was a standup comedian and occasional actor who had a knack for making sound effects with his mouth. He was a fixture on Johnny Carson’s Tonight Show.
A reference to MST3K Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
A line in the offbeat 1971 musical film 200 Motels, written and directed by Frank Zappa, is “Centerville. A real nice place to raise your kids up.”
The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis was a sitcom about the misadventures of all-American teenager Dobie Gillis; the theme song was by Judd Conlon’s Rhythmaires.
Dreadlocks have been found in cultures as diverse as ancient Sparta in Greece and the Maasai tribe of southern Kenya, but the style is now closely associated with the Rastafarian movement.
Adding “Or Is It?” (or just a question mark) to the “The End” title card was briefly in vogue for low-budget sci-fi and horror films in the ‘50s & ‘60s. Manos and The She Creature both used this.
Judy Garland sang this in A Star Is Born, in a scene in which a drunk audience member shouts, “Sing ‘Melancholy Baby’!” It became something of a cliché, making the song the original “Free Bird.”
The “Munster Koach” on the TV sitcom The Munsters was a custom hot rod resembling a hearse built on 3 Ford Model T bodies. It was 18 feet long.
In the north Atlantic, the sun rises above the upper yards, where the square sails hang, around 11 am—a great time for the officers to take a rum break. Landlubbers usually wait until 5 pm.
According to the mythology of the parody religion the Church of the SubGenius and its “founder,” J.R. “Bob” Dobbs, we all need Slack, a loosely defined term that promises a life of ease and leisure.
The Beastmaster is a Conan the Barbarian-type movie starring Marc Singer as a guy who can communicate with animals. It aired seemingly endlessly on HBO, TBS, and TNT.
Walter Brennan was a character actor known for his work in westerns (such as the cantankerous deputy Stumpy in Rio Bravo). He won 3 Oscars for Best Supporting Actor.
Mother Teresa was the founder of the Missionaries of Charity, an order dedicated to helping the poor, particularly in India. She was canonized 19 years after her death.
Did you ever want to learn the meaning behind every reference in the film? Well, now's your chance.
“Vogue” is a 1990 song by Madonna, inspired by the dance of the same name, which was popular in the Harlem “House Ball” scene at that time.
Dr. Smith was a classic example of a coded gay character on ‘60s TV: an effeminate man whose closest friends were a robot and a small boy. (Actor Jonathan Harris, however, was straight.)
An imitation of Frank Sutton as the long-suffering Sgt. Vince Carter on the TV show Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.
Paul Michael Glaser played Detective David Starsky on the TV crime series Starsky & Hutch in the ‘70s.
An imitation of late ‘70s/early ‘80s animated ads for Crest toothpaste about superheroes defending Toothopolis against the Cavity Creeps: grey, rocklike guys who chanted, “We make holes in teeth!”
Herman Munster (played by Fred Gwynne) was the Frankenstein’s monster-ish clan patriarch on The Munsters. Lily was his vampiric spouse, played by Yvonne De Carlo.
Chivas Regal is a 12-year-old blended scotch whisky produced by the Chivas Brothers, which was originally a grocery store and wine merchant in Aberdeen, Scotland.
Mr. Freeze (real name Dr. Victor Fries) is a Batman villain. In the comics his HQ is in a frozen, ice-covered cave.
The Cavity Creeps were typically armed with power drills and pickaxes, but were easily defeated with toothbrushes and Crest toothpaste.
Carlsbad Cavern is an extensive cave complex in southeastern New Mexico, not Arizona. Its passages total nearly a mile in length, and its largest chamber is 33,000 square meters in area.
A towering criminal figure who terrorizes the town in Tom Sawyer, Injun Joe’s secret lair and eventual tomb is McDougal’s Cave; Tom and Becky Thatcher get lost inside it for several days.
Joe Doakes is the careless driver who faces a heavenly trial in the short “X Marks the Spot” in MST3K Episode 210, King Dinosaur. Joe’s only defense: he was nursing a sick friend.
Snap, Crackle, and Pop are the longtime ad icons for Kellogg’s Rice Krispies cereal.
A riff on the classic ‘70s “Hey Mikey!” TV ad for Life cereal that ran for 14 years.
A line from the Bert I. Gordon masterpiece The Amazing Colossal Man, which was riffed in MST3K Episode 309.
A reference to a scene in the film Young Frankenstein, in which the monster awakens noisily in the lab while the others are eating dinner.
An imitation of Gregory Peck as the father of young Antichrist-in-training Damien Thorn in the first of the devil-sploitation film series The Omen.
“The Monsters Are Due on Maple Street” is an episode of The Twilight Zone about a typical small-town street that is destroyed by paranoia over fears of an alien invasion.
In the ‘80s, low-budget TV ads touted a collection of novelty songs for outgoing messages on phone answering machines, then relatively new. These were two of them.
The Paleolithic Era is the period in human prehistory during which mankind’s anatomy and behavior evolved into modern humans (Homo sapiens).
“It Don’t Mean a Thing (If it Ain’t Got That Swing)” is a 1931 jazz standard composed by Duke Ellington. It helped introduce the word “swing” to American pop culture.
Hank Patterson, who plays Hugo the janitor, also played Fred Ziffel, a rural eccentric who was always accompanied by his “son,” a pig named Arnold, on the TV show Green Acres.
Clams casino is an appetizer popular in New England: clams baked with breadcrumbs and bacon and served on the half shell.
The bunny hop is a “novelty dance,” in which dancers form a long, very boisterous line. It was invented in 1952 at Balboa High School in San Francisco.
A line from MST3K Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
Live performances on Pink Floyd’s The Wall tour featured an enormous wall of cardboard bricks that was slowly built throughout the concert and demolished at the end of each show.
An imitation of Mila (played by Lisa Foster) in the film The Blade Master, better known as Cave Dwellers and riffed on in MST3K Episode 301.
In the film Caddyshack, protagonist Danny Noonan is playing in a caddies’ tournament when his fellow caddies try to force him to miss a putt by heckling him from the sidelines.
An imitation of Doug Henning, a mustachioed magician who gained fame in the ‘70s with a Broadway show and became a regular figure on TV with his World of Magic specials.
The eerie sound of the theremin has most notably been used in the films The Day the Earth Stood Still and The Thing from Another World, as well as in some of Led Zeppelin’s most popular songs.
The theremin is the only musical instrument that is played without being touched.
Anne Klein was an American fashion designer who revolutionized the junior clothing market in the 1950s.
A paraphrase of a line from the opening monologue of Patton, taken verbatim from the general’s speech to the Third Army on May 31, 1944, on the eve of D-Day.
When Buddy Ebsen played Jed Clampett on the TV sitcom The Beverly Hillbillies, he sported a battered felt wide-brimmed hat.
Director Bert I. Gordon shamelessly promoted his other films within his own films. In Attack of the Puppet People, for example, The Amazing Colossal Man plays at a drive-in.
Ever since the film’s release, sequels and revivals have been rumored. In 2011, there was even word that a musical was in the works.
In 1978 Kellogg’s introduced Graham Cracko’s cereal with a jingle that sang: “Something new is coming to town and George the Milkman’s bringing it ‘round.”
In “The Cage,” the original pilot of Star Trek, Captain Pike is captured by aliens and caged with the beautiful Vina, who offers to be whatever he wants, saying, “Let me please you.”
That’s the aforementioned Mickey Finn, who played small parts in films and TV shows for nearly 20 years, mostly westerns. He does not appear to be related to Bert.
Among the strangest rumors concerning Doors lead singer Jim Morrison’s death: he was poisoned by spider venom, which he drank as an initiation into an Orphic mystery cult.
John Heard is an actor. One of his best-known roles is as the dad in the Home Alone movies.
Our Town uses a folksy “stage manager” as a narrator, who addresses the audience directly.
Yet more Curly Howard.
For 15 years, Domino’s Pizza offered a 30-minute guarantee, but after paying out nearly $18 million in lawsuits related to accidents caused by speeding delivery drivers, the guarantee was dropped.
The drummer for hard-rock band Def Leppard, Rick “The Thunder God” Allen, lost his left arm in an auto accident in 1984 but continued to play with the band.
A reference to a line in the “Phantom Creeps” short in MST3K Episode 205, Rocket Attack USA.
Dockers is a line of business casual khaki slacks for men, introduced in 1986. They are made by Levi’s.
Primatene Mist is an OTC brand of inhaler used to relieve bronchial asthma. Because it contains CFCs, it was banned in the US after 2011.
An ad slogan for Palmolive soap dating back to the ‘30s was “To make skin soft, smooth, firm yet yielding …”
The Batman villain Penguin (aka Oswald Cobblepot) was played by Burgess Meredith in the ‘60s TV show and by Danny DeVito in the 1992 film Batman Returns.
Pull-tabs could be referencing old-style beverage cans, invented in 1959 by Ermal Fraze.
There have been five official Robins in Batman comics: Dick Grayson, Jason Todd, Tim Drake, Stephanie Brown, and Damian Wayne. Four of them have died.
A riff on a line from surrealistic comedy troupe Firesign Theatre’s last album: In the Next World, You’re on Your Own.
The saying “A rolling stone gathers no moss” dates back to John Heywood’s Proverbs (1546). Its basic meaning goes back to Roman philosopher Publilius Syrus in the 1st century BCE.
“Blue Suede Shoes” is a classic rock song written and recorded by Carl Perkins in 1955. It was covered by Elvis Presley nine months later. The original hit #1, but Elvis’s is better known today.
Earth vs. the Spider: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Jim Morrison frequently emitted a siren scream at live shows, also heard in the recording of “When the Music’s Over.”
Jake and the Fatman was a TV crime series starring William Conrad (the Fatman) and Joe Penny (Jake, average size) that ran on CBS from 1987-92.
Walleyes, northern pike, and lunker largemouth bass are types of fish native to the northern Midwest.
The Bruce Willis box office bomb Hudson Hawk featured broad slapstick accompanied by cartoonish sound effects, occasionally punctuated by a musical duet.
Clark Bar candy bars were first sold in 1917. They were named after inventor David L. Clark.
In the late ‘80s a rumor spread in the tabloids that Michael Jackson had tried to buy the bones of Joseph “Elephant Man” Merrick.
The 1938 Thornton Wilder play Our Town is set in the small town of Grover’s Corners. It was made into a film starring William Holden and Martha Scott in 1940.
Lines from the Neil Young song “Don’t Let It Bring You Down,” from his 1970 album After the Gold Rush.
In Jean-Paul Sartre’s classic work of existential philosophy Being and Nothingness, he famously analyzes the feeling of vertigo you get when you stand at the edge of a precipice.
Justin Wilson was an American chef and humorist known for popularizing Cajun cuisine and for his catchphrase “I gar-on-tee!”
The New Christy Minstrels is a folk music group that helped launch the careers of Kenny Rogers, Kim Carnes, and Gene Clark, among others.
The government initially outlawed tag removal because manufacturers were ripping off the tags to prevent consumers from finding out their mattresses were stuffed with old, gross rags.
A famous line uttered by Michael Keaton as Batman in the 1989 film of the same name.
Six Pack is a 1982 film about a down-on-his-luck race car driver (Rogers) who becomes a reluctant father figure to a group of plucky orphans. Six of them, in fact.
Crazy Days is a two-day event held every July in Buffalo, Minnesota, a small town 40 miles NW of Minneapolis, when local businesses all hold sales.
Cannery Row is a 1945 John Steinbeck novel about the hardscrabble lives of people living by the sardine canneries in Monterey, CA, during the Depression.
The film Ferris Bueller’s Day Off grossed $70 million on a budget of $5.8 million; it was one of the biggest hits of 1986.
Tarantula was a plastic model car kit of a dragster sold in the early ‘70s. They are now considered collector’s items.
There’s no trick to the clown car: it’s just that everything in the car’s interior has been stripped out to provide maximum clown-packing space.
An imitation of Gabby Johnson (Jack Starrett), a parody of perennial western sidekick Gabby Hayes, from the film Blazing Saddles.
By the time devout Rastafarian Bob Marley died, his famous dreadlocks were actually a wig; he was bald due to treatment for a malignant melanoma.
If we missed a reference, be sure to let us know in the comments!
In the animated Christmas special Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, Yukon Cornelius is a prospector who dreams of striking it rich. He was voiced by Larry D. Mann.
A little bit of the show-stopping “Broadway Melody” number in the classic film musical Singin’ in the Rain.
Alan Hale Jr. appeared in three MST3K episodes: 106, The Crawling Hand; 622, Angels Revenge; and 810, The Giant Spider Invasion.
Portuguese explorer Ferdinand Magellan led the first expedition from the Atlantic Ocean into the Pacific Ocean; he died before his fleet finished circumnavigating the globe.
Actor Jack Webb was best known as the unflappable Sgt. Joe Friday on the radio and TV series Dragnet.
“Come into my parlor” is a common misquoting of the 1829 poem “The Spider and the Fly,” by Mary Howitt. The actual line is “‘Will you walk into my parlour?’ said the Spider to the Fly.”
Batman’s utility belt first appeared in Detective Comics #29 in 1939; his first “bat”-themed accessory was the batarang.
A process shot, also known as rear projection, is a special effect in which the actors stand in front of a screen on which an image is being projected.
A reference to a host segment in MST3K Episode 307, Daddy-O.
“Strike a pose” is the lyrical refrain that begins “Vogue.”
A staple of back-of-the-comic-book ads in the ‘50s, ‘60s, & ‘70s, “Funny Black Soap” or “Joke Black Soap” is a normal-looking bar of soap that turns the user’s hands black.
Funeral services, like weddings, often begin with this phrase but then continue with “to pay our final tribute of respect …” or “not to mourn a death, but to celebrate a life …”
The action in The Rockford Files often involved car chases, and one maneuver, a 180-degree J-turn, became known as a “Rockford.”
A reference to the old adage, most likely by lawyer-poet John Godfrey Saxe: “Laws are like sausages, it is better not to see them being made.”
In the comedy-horror film An American Werewolf in London, the hero is warned more than once to “stay on the road. Keep clear of the moors.”
The Yugo was a car manufactured in Yugoslavia (later Serbia). It sold widely in Europe, but it had a poor reputation in the US.
Frank Epperson invented the popsicle by accident in 1905. He originally marketed it as the “Epsicle” but renamed it “Popsicle” thanks to his kids.
Statler and Waldorf are the two cranky old men who heckle from a theater balcony on the TV series The Muppet Show.
A possible reference to the Great Stalacpipe Organ at the Luray Caverns in Virginia. Leland Sprinkle created the world's largest lithophone there in the ‘50s using stalactites hit with mallets.
More Curly Howard noises.
A callback to the “Speech: Using Your Voice” short that began this episode.
Gary Busey is a wild-man actor who has appeared in more than 150 movies. His dad, Delmer Lloyd Busey, is a construction design manager.
“The Cage” never aired, but it was repurposed and made part of a two-part episode in Star Trek’s first season, “The Menagerie.”
Eric Clapton’s cover of Bob Marley’s “I Shot the Sheriff” became Clapton’s only #1 hit song and helped popularize reggae music in general, and Marley in particular, in the US.
The 1985 comedy-adventure film The Goonies is about a group of kids who get drawn into a wild adventure after they discover a pirate treasure map.
On Dialing for Dollars, a local TV host would announce “the count and the amount” and make a random call: if the person had been watching, they would know the answer and win a cash prize.
Calvin Klein jeans ads often feature oiled-up, shirtless guys (and sometimes gals). In the early ‘90s that included a young Mark Wahlberg posing with a topless Kate Moss.
“There Was an Old Lady Who Swallowed a Fly” is a folk song that became a children’s favorite. The best-known version was recorded in 1953 by Burl Ives.
Given the Elks, however, it could also be pull-tab gambling, sometimes used to fundraise. Pull-tab cards are like scratcher lottery cards, but paper panels are removed to reveal the symbols.
An imitation of the often-flustered and tongue-tied Woody Allen, the nebbishy comedian/actor/writer/director whose most famous films include Annie Hall and Manhattan.
A crossed hammer and sickle, representing the unity between industrial and agricultural workers, is a well-known Communist symbol.
Jack Weston was a heavyset character actor known for comedic roles. He played the resort owner in Dirty Dancing and an OCD dentist in The Four Seasons.
Curly Howard, B. Jerome Lester Horwitz, was a vaudeville performer and comic actor best known as one of The Three Stooges, along with brother Moe Howard and actor Larry Fine.
Mortimer Snerd was a ventriloquist’s dummy, the slow-witted friend of wisecracking Charlie McCarthy. Both were given voice by ventriloquist Edgar Bergen.
Soap box racers were first made in the early ‘30s by kids who attached wheels to empty wooden orange crates. Now the sophisticated vehicles are made from fiberglass and reach speeds of 35 mph.
A line from the film The Wizard of Oz: the Wicked Witch of the West enchants Dorothy and her friends to run through a field of poppies, causing them to fall into a drugged sleep.
In a classic ‘80s Massengill douche ad, a mom and daughter discuss feminine hygiene. The famous line: “Mom, do you ever feel, you know, not so fresh?”
In the PSA, a small boy mimics his father as they do everyday chores—and when he lights up a smoke. The V.O. then says, “Like father, like son? Think about it.”
First cast as a villain on Lost in Space, stowaway Dr. Zachary Smith (Jonathan Harris) soon became a sympathetic character and comic relief.
Billed as “The World’s Greatest Drummer,” Buddy Rich was an American jazz percussionist much admired for his speed and technique.
An oft-quoted line from the Arnold Schwarzenegger film Commando: “Remember, Sully, when I promised to kill you last? I lied.”
In the children’s novel Charlotte’s Web, the spider Charlotte saves the young pig Wilbur from becoming dinner by spelling out words in her web, including the famous “SOME PIG.”
After WWII, a number of Japanese soldiers continued to hide in the jungle and fight in the Pacific. The last Japanese “holdout” surrendered in 1974.
The opening scene of the movie Patton has George C. Scott as Patton delivering his famous speech to the Third Army in front of an enormous American flag.
Beatrice “Aunt Bee” Taylor (played by Frances Bavier) was Sheriff Andy Taylor’s aunt on The Andy Griffith Show. She made a mean butterscotch pecan pie (Opie’s favorite).
Bert I. Gordon’s wife, Flora M. Gordon, worked on special effects for a number of her husband’s movies. Tonka is a popular toy manufacturer best known for its line of trucks.
A line from The Wizard of Oz, spoken to Dorothy by the Scarecrow, signaling the arrival of Glinda, the Good Witch of the North.
Dr. Laurence Erhardt, played by Josh “J. Elvis” Weinstein, was Dr. Forrester’s original sidekick. Weinstein went on to become a writer in LA (Freaks and Geeks, America’s Funniest Home Videos).
Hunan beef is a popular menu item in Chinese restaurants. The spicy dish involves thin-sliced beef, chile peppers, garlic, soy sauce, and rice wine.
Spencer Gifts—now just Spencer’s—is a mall retailer targeting 12- to 25-year-olds with clothing, band merch, gag gifts, room décor, etc.
The video for the Don Henley song “The Boys of Summer,” filmed in black-and-white French New Wave style, featured many shirtless, sweaty men.
Country singer/sausage entrepreneur Jimmy Ray Dean’s TV show, The Jimmy Dean Show, gave America its first glimpse at the work of puppeteer Jim Henson.
In the sci-fi film Terminator 2: Judgment Day, Arnold Schwarzenegger says the evil T-1000 Terminator (played by Robert Patrick) is made of “liquid metal.”
In the WB short “Hook, Line and Stinker,” Wile E. Coyote unrolls a bundle of dynamite and places it under an overpass; it rolls back up unseen to his hiding place, and—boom.
A little bit of the show-stopping “Broadway Melody” number in the classic film musical Singin’ in the Rain.
Rose Kennedy was the matriarch of “Camelot”—the mother of 9 children, including President John F. Kennedy and Senators Robert and Ted. She lived to be 104.
Attack of the Puppet People was later riffed on by Mike Nelson, Kevin Murphy, and Bill Corbett as part of RiffTrax.
Russian composer Igor Stravinsky created many of the classic works of modernism, including his ballet The Rite of Spring, which caused a near-riot when it premiered in Paris.
The TV sitcom Green Acres starred Eddie Albert as Oliver Douglas, a big-city man trying to adapt to life on a farm. Eb Dawson was a dimwitted farmhand who called Douglas “Dad.”
Aqua Velva is a men’s aftershave introduced in 1929. In 2010 its traditional glass bottles were replaced with plastic, reportedly at customer request.
Bert I. Gordon has the distinction of being the single director with the most movies featured on MST3K (eight).
Anxious Edge is a 1990 album (and title song) from British pop singer David Grant, who had several hits in the ‘80s.
Towns throughout the South and Midwest have tornado warning sirens that wail to indicate a tornado watch, warning, or emergency. Generally the siren sounds the same for any of these events.
Acerbic comedian Dennis Miller has appeared on numerous TV series and hosted several talk shows. His act is marked by harshly critical takes on American culture and politics.
The tailfins in ‘50s cars were purely stylistic, associated with the rocketry of the Space Age. They had nothing to do with mileage, although Plymouth claimed they stabilized the car in crosswinds.
H.L. Mencken was a journalist known for his scathing wit. He famously reported on the Scopes Monkey Trial for the Baltimore Sun.
Singer/actor Al Jolson, a white man, performed his signature song, “My Mammy,” on bended knee, and, of course, in blackface (which was a perfectly acceptable show-biz thing back then).
Archaeologists have found centuries-old graffiti in the ruins of Pompeii saying things like “Daphnus was here with his Felicia.” The impulse is universal, apparently.
Stuart Pankin is a character actor who played anchor Bob Charles on HBO’s Not Necessarily the News and Sheriff Lloyd Parsons in Arachnophobia, among many others.
Possibly a reference to the name blues legend B.B. King gave to all his guitars, which were usually variants on the Gibson ES-355.
Let us know if we missed any references!
Them! was an early (and really quite good) example of the “radiation-spawned big bug” movies, about giant radioactive ants trashing LA; it starred James “Gunsmoke” Arness.
Just how electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) works remains a mystery, but it has proved effective in treating severe depression that does not respond to medication or other therapies.

In the Jules Verne novel A Journey to the Center of the Earth, Arne Saknussemm is a medieval explorer. He carves “A.S.” in the walls of the tunnels leading to the lost world, showing the correct path.
“Ding-dong, Avon calling” was an ad slogan for the direct-sales cosmetics company Avon from 1954-67.
Farah slacks were a line of wrinkle-free bell-bottom trousers that became very popular in the late ‘70s. You can see them in the opening sequence of the film Saturday Night Fever.
Legs Diamond is one of the greatest Broadway flops in history, a 1989 musical about a gangster who dreams of making it big on Broadway. There is also a rock band by that name.
Andy Rooney was a journalist best known for his blandly witty commentaries, delivered at a desk, which concluded the TV news show 60 Minutes from 1978-2011.
The Meal Maker is a kitchen appliance, made by Hamilton Beach, that is a slow cooker, steamer, and deep fryer in one. Now, how much would you pay?
The charismatic Lech Walesa cofounded Poland’s Solidarity, the first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc, and was president of Poland from 1990-95.
“Cha-cha” is a term that Dennis Miller sometimes tags onto the end of a sentence, in a vague imitation of Sammy Davis Jr.
“You can never be too rich or too thin” is a maxim that is usually credited to Wallis Simpson, the Duchess of Windsor, though that attribution is shaky.
She’s the Sheriff was a short-lived syndicated sitcom starring Suzanne Somers, her first TV role after walking out on Three’s Company.
The first detonation of an atomic bomb took place in the desert north of Alamogordo, NM, on July 16, 1945. Alamogordo is about 100 miles from Carlsbad Caverns.
A reference to MST3K Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
In the ancient Roman pantheon, Neptune (Greek equivalent: Poseidon) was usually depicted holding a trident, a three-pronged spear used for spear-fishing.
Today this phrase is strongly associated with The Simpsons’ Chief Wiggum, but it goes much further back, to the 1965 Perry Mason episode “The Case of the Silent Six.”
Garrison Keillor is an author and storyteller best known as the host of the old-timey radio show A Prairie Home Companion on NPR.
Now let us entertain you with…the fully-annotated Earth vs. the Spider!
Sports Illustrated has been publishing the annual “Swimsuit Issue” since 1964. The first cover model was Babette March.
The first part seems to be an imitation of The Three Stooges’ Curly Howard. The second part could be comedian Charlie Callas.
A paraphrase of the famous credit line “No animals were harmed in the making of this film,” which is copyrighted by the American Humane Association.
Bert I. Gordon, aka Mr. B.I.G., is a director known for his low-budget sci-fi and horror films in the ‘50s and ‘60s.
DDT (an abbreviation for dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane) is an industrial insecticide. It was banned in the US in 1972 due to concerns over its environmental impact.
In 1903 a Chicago bartender named Mickey Finn was arrested for drugging and robbing his customers—the probable origin of the slang term. “Fin” is also slang for a $5 bill.
Early mummies have very little scent, apart from a slight mustiness. Later mummies smell of the resin used to preserve them.
Pre-Internet, 900 phone numbers were intensely marketed and very popular. With charges starting at $3 per minute, they offered phone sex, psychic hotlines, and more.
The Flying Wallendas is a group of high wire circus performers famous for working without a net, which has killed several of them, including their founder.
In the ‘50s, there briefly was a fourth mascot, Pow, who represented the “power of whole-grain rice.” He wore a space helmet.
For playing the Joker in the 1989 Batman, Jack Nicholson received a large percentage of the box office gross, as well as (reportedly) a cut of the sequels. He may have gotten $60-$90 million.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Convoy is a 1978 film that indeed stars Kristofferson and MacGraw, and was directed by Sam Peckinpah; it is a prime example of the then-popular CB radio/trucker genre.
Industrial Light & Magic has provided visual effects for nearly 300 films and won 15 Oscars since George Lucas founded it to create special effects for Star Wars.
Frank Sinatra Jr. is the son of the famous crooner. At the age of 19, Sinatra the Younger was kidnapped and released two days later after a ransom was paid.
Road House is a 1989 movie starring Patrick Swayze as a bouncer in a dive bar; it was one of the writers’ favorites.
Actress Brenda Vaccaro is best known for the films Midnight Cowboy and Airport ’77 and her many guest appearances in TV shows such as The Love Boat and The Golden Girls.
A line from the rock standard “Hey Joe.” In 2016, a Guinness world record was set in Wroclaw, Poland, when 7,356 guitarists played “Hey Joe” simultaneously.
A reference to the old adage, most likely by lawyer-poet John Godfrey Saxe: “Laws are like sausages, it is better not to see them being made.”
Batman #12 referred to “secret underground hangars,” but it was the Batman movie serials that introduced the crime-lab-in-a-cave and secret entrances, as well as the term “Batcave.”
In the film Jaws, Police Chief Brody wants to close the beaches to protect the public but is overruled by the mayor, who wants to keep the tourist revenue rolling in.
Herbalife is a line of nutrition, weight loss, and beauty products distributed through an MLM network (which some have called a pyramid scheme) similar to Amway’s.
An imitation of the titles on The NBC Mystery Movie, an umbrella title for rotating TV shows that aired in the same time slot: the first shows were Columbo, McMillan & Wife, and McCloud.
In Australia and New Zealand, Rice Krispies are called Rice Bubbles.
“Spider” John Koerner is a Minneapolis singer/songwriter/guitarist. Bob Dylan cites him as an early influence.
Just how fat was the Fatman? At one point actor William Conrad was up to 290 lbs. He lost about 50 lbs. at one point, but he was back up to 260 by his death (from congestive heart failure) in 1994.
A tanning bed is a coffin-like contraption that emits UV radiation to produce a tan. They are less popular now, but there are more than 10,000 locations offering them in the US alone.
Let no one forget the grasshopper falling off the picture of a building in MST3K Episode 517, Beginning of the End.
Did we somehow miss a reference? Drop us a line in the comments!
“Spy vs. Spy” is a comic strip created by Antonio Prohías for Mad magazine. It features two pointy-beaked spies, one white and the other black, constantly plotting against each other.
Although Alan Hale Sr. and his son Alan Hale Jr. were both actors and near lookalikes, this is probably referring to Jr., best known for playing the Skipper on Gilligan’s Island.
Knucklehead Smiff was a ventriloquist dummy brought to life by voice actor and comedian Paul Winchell in the early years of TV.
“I Love a Parade” is a lively song composed in 1931 for the film Manhattan Parade by Harold Arlen and Ted Koehler.
“Action Slacks” is a brand name for Levi’s men’s casual polyester slacks, which were discontinued in 2011.
